         <abstract>
            <p>Single-step discretization methods are considered for equations of the form $u_t + Au = f(t, u)$, where $A$ is a linear positive definite operator in a Hilbert space $H$. It is shown that if the method is consistent with the differential equation then the convergence is essentially of first order in the stepsize, even if the initial data $v$ are only in $H$, but also that, in contrast to the situation in the linear homogeneous case, higher-order convergence is not possible in general without further assumptions on $v$.</p>
          </abstract>
